<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><U>Other
Compensation</U> </FONT></P>

<UL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Non-business
related flights on corporate aircraft are covered by time-sharing lease agreements, pursuant to which certain costs associated with those flights are reimbursed in
accordance with Federal Aviation Administration regulations. Messrs.&nbsp;White and Freyman have such agreements and reimbursed Abbott for non-business flights in accordance with those
agreements. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
following amounts are included in the totals in this column, which reflect Abbott's incremental cost less reimbursements for non-business related flights, M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White:
$151,885&nbsp;/ $139,683&nbsp;/ $103,292; and T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman: $344&nbsp;/ $1,138&nbsp;/ $0. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Abbott
determines the incremental cost for these flights based on the direct cost to Abbott, including fuel costs, parking, handling and landing fees, catering, travel fees, and other miscellaneous
direct costs. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Included
in the totals shown in this column are costs associated with security for 2009 and 2008, respectively: M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White: $300,193&nbsp;/ $180,467; T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman:
$0&nbsp;/ $38,309; and L.&nbsp;J.&nbsp;Schumacher: $0&nbsp;/ $10,697. Abbott determines the cost for these expenses based on its actual costs. The security is provided on the recommendation of
an independent security study. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Also
included in the totals shown in the table is the cost of providing a corporate automobile less the amount reimbursed by the executive: M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White: $0&nbsp;/ $0&nbsp;/ $7,344;
T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman: $10,933&nbsp;/ $10,654&nbsp;/ $7,364; O.&nbsp;Bohuon: $22,555; and L.&nbsp;J.&nbsp;Schumacher: $18,509&nbsp;/ $21,093; and J.&nbsp;V.&nbsp;Mazzo: $14,817. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher, costs associated with financial planning are included: $10,000&nbsp;/ $10,000. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon, tax equalization payments of $397,417 paid by Abbott to avoid double taxation relating to his work in France and the United States are included. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo, pursuant to the terms of the employment agreement described in footnote 9&nbsp;the following amounts are included: (i)&nbsp;a $2,325,000 cash payment, payable when Abbott
acquired Advanced Medical Optics,&nbsp;Inc. ("AMO"); (ii)&nbsp;a $2,325,000 cash payment, payable on the six-month anniversary of Abbott's acquisition of AMO and contingent on his
continued employment; and, (iii)&nbsp;as contemplated under his previous AMO employment agreement, tax gross-ups on these payments of $2,031,951. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
named officers are also eligible to participate in an executive disability benefit described on page&nbsp;34. </FONT></P>

</UL>
</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(7)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Because
French employment relationships are contractual, Abbott has an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon. It provides that he will be the Executive Vice President, Abbott
Pharmaceutical Products, fixes his base salary at 576,388&nbsp;Euro per year, which will be reviewed and adjusted annually, and that he will participate in the 1998 Abbott Laboratories Performance
Incentive Plan. To perform his duties, Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon frequently must travel between the United States and France and was subject to tax in both countries. His employment agreement is designed to
mitigate the impact of this double taxation. Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon receives the French Retirement Indemnity, social security pensions and other benefit programs applicable to local French employees.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(8)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon
is employed in France. All of the amounts reported on the table for Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon that were paid in Euro were converted to U.S.&nbsp;dollars at the
December&nbsp;31, 2009 exchange rate of 1.43&nbsp;U.S.&nbsp;dollars to the Euro, with the exception of his performance-based bonus under the 1998 Abbott Laboratories Performance
Incentive Plan, which was converted at the February&nbsp;19, 2010&nbsp;exchange rate of 1.35&nbsp;U.S.&nbsp;dollars to the Euro.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(9)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
connection with its acquisition of Advanced Medical Optics, Inc. ("AMO"), Abbott entered an agreement with J.&nbsp;V.&nbsp;Mazzo, AMO's chairman and chief executive officer.
Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo's agreement with Abbott provides he will serve as Senior Vice President, President, AMO, set his initial base salary at $775,000, and provides that future salary increases will be
based on merit according to overall performance and in line with Abbott's performance and merit criteria in accordance with other similarly situated officers of Abbott. In place of the payments due to
him under the change in control provisions of his previous AMO&nbsp;employment agreement, the agreement provides that he receive: (i)&nbsp;a $2,325,000 cash payment, plus a tax
gross-up, as contemplated under his previous AMO employment agreement, payable when Abbott acquired AMO; (ii)&nbsp;a $2,325,000 cash payment, plus an additional tax gross-up,
as contemplated under his previous AMO&nbsp;employment agreement, payable on the six-month anniversary of Abbott's acquisition of AMO and contingent on his continued employment;
(iii)&nbsp;a $1,500,000 cash payment, plus an additional tax gross-up, payable on the first anniversary of Abbott's acquisition of AMO and contingent on his continued employment; and,
(iv)&nbsp;a $1,500,000 cash payment plus an additional tax gross-up, on the eighteen month anniversary of Abbott's acquisition of AMO and contingent on his continued employment. It also
provides that he is eligible to participate in Abbott's performance incentive plan, with a participation target of 100% of his base salary.
Pursuant to the agreement, he was also granted 30,000 shares of restricted stock which vest ratably over three years and 20,000 shares of restricted stock of Abbott, which will vest after eighteen
months of employment. These shares of restricted stock are described in the 2009&nbsp;Grants of Plan-Based Awards table on page&nbsp;21. </FONT></DD></DL>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(1)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Each
of the named officers participates in the 1998&nbsp;Abbott Laboratories Performance Incentive Plan, an annual, non-equity incentive plan. The annual cash incentive
award earned by the named officer in 2009 under the plan is shown in the Summary Compensation Table under the column captioned "Non-Equity Incentive Plan Compensation." No future payouts
will be made under the plan's 2009&nbsp;annual cash incentive award. The Performance Incentive Plan is described in greater detail in the section of the proxy statement captioned, "Compensation
Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#150; Compensation Components&nbsp;&#150; Performance-Based Annual Cash Incentives."
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(2)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are performance-based restricted stock awards that have a 5-year term and vest upon Abbott reaching a minimum return on equity target, with no more than
one-third of the award vesting in any one year. In 2009, Abbott reached its minimum return on equity target and one-third of each of the awards made on February&nbsp;20,
2009, vested on February&nbsp;26, 2010. The equity targets are described in the section of the proxy statement captioned, "Compensation Discussion and Analysis&nbsp;&#150; Compensation
Components&nbsp;&#150; Long-Term Incentives&nbsp;&#150; Equity Awards."
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(3)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
the event of a grantee's death or disability or a change in control of Abbott, as defined in Abbott Laboratories' Incentive Stock programs, these awards are deemed fully earned.
Outstanding restricted shares receive dividends at the same rate as all other shareholders.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(4)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are restricted shares granted as a retention award and will vest on August&nbsp;26, 2010.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(5)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are restricted shares granted as a retention award. One-third of these shares vested on February&nbsp;26, 2010. An additional third will vest on February&nbsp;26, 2011. The
final third will vest on February&nbsp;26, 2012.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(6)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>One-third
of the shares covered by these options are exercisable after one year; two-thirds after two years; and all after three years. The options vest in the
event of the grantee's death or disability or a change in control of Abbott. Under the Abbott Laboratories 1996&nbsp;Incentive Stock Program, these options have an exercise price equal to the
average of the high and low market prices (rounded-up to the next even penny) of an Abbott common share on the date of grant. These options do not contain a replacement option feature.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(7)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Abbott
determines the grant date fair value of stock awards by multiplying the number of restricted shares granted by the average of the high and low market prices of an Abbott common
share on the grant date.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(8)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
values were determined as of the option's grant date using a Black-Scholes stock option valuation model. The model uses the assumptions described in Note&nbsp;9,
entitled "Incentive Stock Program" of Abbott's Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements included under Item&nbsp;8, "Financial Statements and Supplemental Data" in Abbott's 2009&nbsp;Annual
Report on Securities and Exchange Commission Form&nbsp;10-K. </FONT>
<BR><BR>
</DD></DL>

</TR>
<TR VALIGN="TOP">
<TD COLSPAN=22 VALIGN="BOTTOM" style="font-family:;"><HR NOSHADE></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!-- end of user-specified TAGGED TABLE -->

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-9pt;'><FONT SIZE=1>(i)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=1>Advanced
Medical Optics, Inc. ("AMO") granted these options to J.&nbsp;V.&nbsp;Mazzo prior to AMO's acquisition by Abbott. As part of the acquisition, Abbott assumed all of AMO's
outstanding and unexercised stock options and converted them into options to purchase Abbott common shares. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=1>See also footnotes on pages&nbsp;27 and 28. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<A NAME="page_ea44701_1_28"> </A>
<BR><BR>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(a)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are the restricted shares that remained outstanding and unvested on December&nbsp;31, 2009, from an award made on February&nbsp;16, 2007. The award has a 5-year
term, with no more than one-third of the original award vesting in any one year upon Abbott reaching a minimum return on equity target, measured at the end of the relevant year. In 2009,
Abbott reached its minimum return on equity target and these shares vested on February&nbsp;26, 2010.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(b)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are the restricted shares that remained outstanding and unvested on December&nbsp;31, 2009, from an award made on February&nbsp;15, 2008. The award has a 5-year
term with no more than one-third of the original award vesting in any one year upon Abbott reaching a minimum equity target, measured at the end of the relevant year. In 2009, Abbott
reached its minimum return on equity target and one-half of the unvested shares vested on February&nbsp;26, 2010.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(c)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are the restricted shares that remained outstanding and unvested on December&nbsp;31, 2009, from an award made on February&nbsp;20, 2009. The award has a 5-year
term, with no more than one-third of the original award vesting in any one year upon Abbott reaching a minimum return on equity target, measured at the end of the relevant year. In 2009,
Abbott reached its minimum return on equity target and one third of these shares vested on February&nbsp;26, 2010.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(d)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>These
are the restricted shares that remained outstanding and unvested on December&nbsp;31, 2009, from an award made on August&nbsp;1, 2009. The award has a 5-year
term, with no more than one-third of the original award vesting in any one year upon Abbott reaching a minimum return on equity target, measured at the end of the relevant year. In 2009,
Abbott reached its minimum return on equity target and one third of these shares will vest on August&nbsp;1, 2010. </FONT></DD></DL>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=34,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=636114,FOLIO='29',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EC44701A.;9',USER='MWEINST',CD=';4-MAR-2010;11:52' -->

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="page_ee44701_1_30"> </A> </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_BASECOLOR,"Black" -->




<!-- COMMAND=ADD_DEFAULTFONT,"font-family:;" -->


 </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Pension Benefits  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The named officers, other than Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon, participate in two Abbott-sponsored defined benefit pension plans: the Abbott Laboratories Annuity Retirement Plan, a tax-qualified
pension plan; and the Abbott Laboratories Supplemental Pension Plan, a non-qualified supplemental pension plan. Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon participates in the Retirement Indemnity pension for
Abbott's eligible employees in France who are covered by the Syntec Convention Collective agreement. Abbott has adopted the Supplemental Pension Plan to provide the portion of the Annuity Retirement
Plan benefit that cannot be paid from the Annuity Retirement Plan due to the pay and benefit amount limitations set by the Internal Revenue Code. The Supplemental Pension Plan also includes a benefit
feature Abbott uses to attract officers who are at the mid-point of their career. This feature provides an additional benefit that is most valuable to officers who are
mid-career hires and is less valuable to officers who have spent most of their career at Abbott. Except as provided in Abbott's change in control agreements, Abbott does not have a policy
granting extra years of credited service under the plans. These change in control agreements are described on pages&nbsp;34 and&nbsp;35. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
compensation considered in determining the pensions payable to the named officers, other than Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon, is the compensation shown in the "Salary" and "Non-Equity Incentive
Plan Compensation" columns of the Summary Compensation Table on page&nbsp;18. The compensation considered in determining the pension payable to Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon is the compensation shown in the
"Salary" column of that table. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Annuity Retirement Plan  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The Annuity Retirement Plan covers most employees in the United States, age&nbsp;21 or older and provides participants with a life annuity benefit at normal retirement equal to A plus the greater of
B or C below. </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>A.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>1.10%
of 5-year final average earnings multiplied by years of benefit service after 2003.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>B.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>1.65%
of 5-year final average earnings multiplied by years of benefit service prior to 2004 (up to 20); plus 1.50% of 5-year final average earnings multiplied
by years of benefit service prior to 2004 in excess of 20 (but no more than 15 additional years); less </FONT></DD></DL>
<UL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>0.50%
of the lesser of 3-year final average earnings (but not more than the social security wage base in any year) or the social security covered compensation level multiplied by years of
benefit service. </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>C.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>1.10%
of 5-year final average earnings multiplied by years of benefit service prior to 2004. </FONT></DD></DL>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
benefit for service prior to 2004 (B or C above) is reduced for the cost of preretirement surviving spouse benefit protection. The reduction is calculated using formulas based on age and
employment status during the period in which coverage was in effect. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Final
average earnings are the average of the 60 highest-paid consecutive calendar months of compensation (salary and non-equity incentive plan compensation) out of the last
120&nbsp;months worked. The Annuity Retirement Plan covers earnings up to the limit imposed by Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17) and provides for a maximum of 35&nbsp;years of
benefit service. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Participants
become fully vested in their pension benefit upon the completion of five years of service. The benefit is payable on an unreduced basis at age&nbsp;65. Employees hired after 2003 who
terminate prior to age&nbsp;55 with at least 10&nbsp;years of service may choose to commence their benefits on an actuarially reduced basis as early as age&nbsp;55. Employees hired prior to 2004
who terminate prior to age&nbsp;50 with at least 10&nbsp;years of service may choose to commence their benefits on an actuarially reduced basis as early as age&nbsp;50. Employees hired prior to
2004 who terminate prior to age&nbsp;50 with less than 10&nbsp;years of service may choose to commence their benefits on an actuarially reduced basis as early as age&nbsp;55. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Annuity Retirement Plan offers several optional forms of payment, including certain and life annuities, joint and survivor annuities, and level income annuities. The benefit paid under any of
these options is actuarially equivalent to the life annuity benefit produced by the formula described above. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Employees
who retire from Abbott prior to their normal retirement age may receive subsidized early retirement benefits. Employees hired after 2003 are eligible for early retirement at age&nbsp;55
with 10&nbsp;years of service. Employees hired prior to 2004 are eligible for early retirement at age&nbsp;50 with 10&nbsp;years of service or age&nbsp;55 if the employee's age plus years of
benefit service total 70 or more. Messrs.&nbsp;White and Freyman are eligible for early retirement benefits under the plan. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
subsidized early retirement reductions applied to the benefit payable for service after 2003 (A&nbsp;above) depend upon the participant's age at retirement. If the participant retires after
reaching age&nbsp;55, the benefit is reduced 5&nbsp;percent per year for each year that payments are made before age&nbsp;62. If the participant retires after reaching age&nbsp;50 but prior to
reaching age&nbsp;55, the benefit is actuarially reduced from age&nbsp;65. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
early retirement reductions applied to the benefit payable for service prior to 2004 (B and C above) depend upon age and service at retirement: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
general, the 5-year final average earnings portions of the benefit are reduced 3&nbsp;percent per year for each year that payments are made before
age&nbsp;62 and the 3-year final average earnings portion of the benefit is reduced 5&nbsp;percent per year for each year that payments are made before age&nbsp;62. </FONT></DD></DL>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>30</FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=35,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=619306,FOLIO='30',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EE44701A.;11',USER='MWEINST',CD=';4-MAR-2010;11:52' -->
<A NAME="page_ee44701_1_31"> </A>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Employees
who participated in the plan before age&nbsp;36 may elect "Special Retirement" on the last day of any month after reaching age&nbsp;55 with age plus Seniority
Service points of at least 94 or "Early Special Retirement" on the last day of any month after reaching age&nbsp;55 provided their age plus Seniority Service points would reach at least 94 before
age&nbsp;65. Seniority service includes periods of employment prior to attaining the minimum age required to participate in the plan. If Special Retirement or Early Special Retirement applies,
seniority service is used in place of benefit service in the formulas. The 5-year final average earnings portions of the benefit in B above are reduced 1<SUP>2</SUP>/<SMALL>3</SMALL>&nbsp;percent
for each year between ages&nbsp;59 and 62 plus 2<SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>2</SMALL>&nbsp;percent for each year between ages&nbsp;55 and 59. The 3-year final average earnings portion of the benefit is
reduced 5&nbsp;percent per year for each year that payments are made before age&nbsp;62. Benefit&nbsp;C is payable on an unreduced basis at Special Retirement and is reduced 3&nbsp;percent per
year for each year that payments are made before age&nbsp;62, if Early Special Retirement applies. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Supplemental Pension Plan  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
With the following exceptions, the provisions of the Supplemental Pension Plan are substantially the same as those of the Annuity Retirement Plan: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Officers'
5-year final average earnings are calculated using the average of the 5 highest years of base earnings and the 5 highest years of payments under
Abbott's non-equity incentive plans.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Annuity Retirement Plan does not include amounts deferred or payments received under the Abbott Laboratories Deferred Compensation Plan in its calculation of a
participant's final average earnings. To preserve the pension benefits of Deferred Compensation Plan participants, the Supplemental Pension Plan includes amounts deferred by a participant under the
Deferred Compensation Plan in its
calculation of final average earnings. Beginning in the year following their election as an officer, Abbott officers are no longer eligible to defer compensation under the Deferred Compensation Plan.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
addition to the benefits outlined above for the Annuity Retirement Plan, officers are eligible for a benefit equal to 0.6% of 5-year final average earnings
for each year of service for each of the first 20&nbsp;years of service occurring after the participant attains age 35. The benefit is further limited by the maximum percentage allowed under the
Annuity Retirement Plan under that plan's benefit formulas (A, B and C above). The portion of this additional officer benefit attributable to service prior to 2004 is reduced 3&nbsp;percent per year
for each year that payments are made before age 60. The portion attributable to service after 2003 is reduced 5&nbsp;percent per year for each year that payments are made before age 60 if the
participant is at least age 55 at early retirement. If the participant is under age 55 at retirement, the portion attributable to service after 2003 is actuarially reduced from age 65.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Supplemental Pension Plan provides early retirement benefits similar to those provided under the Annuity Retirement Plan. The benefits provided to officers under the
Supplemental Pension Plan are not, however, reduced for the period between age 60 and age 62, unless the benefit is being actuarially reduced from age 65. Messrs.&nbsp;White and Freyman are eligible
for early retirement benefits under the plan.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Vested
plan benefits accrued under the Supplemental Pension Plan may be funded through a grantor trust established by the officer. Consistent with the distribution
requirements of Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;409A and its regulations, those officers who were elected prior to 2009 may have the entire amount of their vested plan benefits funded through a
grantor trust. Officers elected after 2008 may only have the vested plan benefits that accrue following the calendar year in which the officer is first elected funded through a grantor trust. Vested
plan benefits accrued through December&nbsp;31, 2008, to the extent not previously funded, were distributed to the participants' individual trusts and included in the participants' income. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Benefits
payable under the Supplemental Pension Plan are offset by the benefits payable from the Annuity Retirement Plan, calculated as if benefits under the plans commenced at the same time. The
amounts paid to an officer's Supplemental Pension Plan grantor trust to fund plan benefits are actuarially determined. The plan is designed to result in Abbott paying the officer's Supplemental
Pension Plan benefits to the extent assets held in the officer's trust are insufficient. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Retirement Indemnity Pension  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The Retirement Indemnity pension provides a lump sum payment to eligible Abbott employees in France who are covered by the Syntec Convention Collective agreement. Since Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon has more than
five years of service with the company, on retirement he would receive a payment equal to one month's salary (based on the average of his base salary paid during the twelve-month period preceding the
date of retirement) plus one-fifth of a month's base salary multiplied by his years of service in excess of five years. To receive a payment, at retirement the participant must be at least
60&nbsp;years old, eligible for an unreduced French Social Security pension, and employed by an Abbott entity governed by the Syntec Convention Collective agreement. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(1)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Abbott
calculates these present values using: (i)&nbsp;a 6.11% discount rate, the same discount rate it uses for Financial Accounting Standards Board ASC Topic&nbsp;715
calculations for financial reporting purposes; and (ii)&nbsp;each plan's unreduced retirement age, which is age 62 under the Abbott Laboratories Annuity Retirement Plan and age 60 under the Abbott
Laboratories Supplemental Pension Plan for those officers who are eligible for early retirement benefits and is age&nbsp;65 under both plans for other officers. The present values shown in the table
reflect postretirement mortality, based on the Financial Accounting Standards Board ASC Topic&nbsp;715 assumption (the RP2000 Combined Healthy table), but do not include a factor for preretirement
termination, mortality, or disability.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(2)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Consistent
with the distribution requirements of Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;409A and its regulations, vested Supplemental Pension Plan benefits, to the extent not previously
funded, were distributed to the participants' individual grantor trusts and included in the participants' income. Amounts held in the officer's individual trust are expected to offset Abbott's
obligations to the officer under the plan. During 2009, the amounts shown, less applicable tax withholdings, were deposited in such individual trusts established by the named officers.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(3)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
present value of Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon's accumulated benefit was converted from Euro to U.S. dollars at the December&nbsp;31, 2009 exchange rate of 1.43&nbsp;U.S.&nbsp;dollars
to the Euro. </FONT></DD></DL>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(1)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Employee
contributions to the Executive Deferred Compensation Plan stopped in 2004.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(2)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
plan permits participants to defer up to 100% of their base salary and annual cash incentives and credited a participant's account with an amount equal to the employer matching
contributions that would have been made for the participant under AMO's tax-qualified defined contribution plan, if certain Internal Revenue Code limitations did not apply.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(3)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Under
the plans, Participants may direct the investment of their deferral account into one or more of several funds chosen by the administrator, and their deferral account is credited
with investment returns based on the performance of the fund(s) selected. During 2009, the weighted average rate of return credited to Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo's accounts was 17.5&nbsp;percent.<BR></FONT>
<BR>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
plans permit cash distributions either in the form of a lump sum payment or installments upon retirement (defined as age 55 with a minimum of five years of service, or age 65 with a minimum of one
year of service), termination of employment, or death. Participants make distribution elections each year, prior to any deferrals being made for that year, and only for the deferrals to be made in the
following calendar year. Under the 2005 plan, Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo's distributions must also comply with the requirements of Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;409A. Participants may make withdrawals
due to financial hardship, with the amount being limited to the amount needed to address the hardship. </FONT></P>

</DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(4)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amounts reported in this column are not included in the Summary Compensation Table.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>(5)</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Because
Abbott acquired AMO in 2009, none of the amounts included in this column have been previously reported as compensation in Abbott's prior Summary Compensation Tables. </FONT></DD></DL>

</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Potential Payments Upon Termination&nbsp;&#150; Generally  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Abbott does not have employment agreements with Messrs.&nbsp;White or Freyman, or Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher. Abbott's agreements with Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon and Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo are described in
footnotes&nbsp;7 and 9, respectively, of the Summary Compensation Table on page&nbsp;18. Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon's agreement provides that upon termination of employment by Abbott, other than for gross
or willful misconduct, he will be paid the amounts described below. Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo's agreement does not provide for payments upon termination or a change in control. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
following summarizes the payments that the named officers, other than Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon, would have received if their employment had terminated on December&nbsp;31, 2009. Earnings, fees, and tax
payments would have continued to be paid for the named officer's Performance Incentive Plan, Management Incentive Plan, and Supplemental 401(k)&nbsp;Plan grantor trusts, until the trust assets were
fully distributed and fees would have continued to be paid for the named officer's Supplemental Pension Plan grantor trust, until its assets were fully distributed. The amount of these payments would
depend on the period over which the trusts' assets were distributed, tax rates, and the trusts' earnings and
fees. If the trusts' assets were distributed over a ten-year period and based on current tax rates, earnings, and fees, the named officers would receive the following average annual
payments over such 10-year period: M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White, $796,339; T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman, $69,753; and, L.&nbsp;J.&nbsp;Schumacher, $181,233. In addition, the following
one-time deposits would have been made under the Abbott Laboratories Supplemental Pension Plan for each of the following named officers, respectively, M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White,
$2,730,902; T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman, $1,933,148; L.&nbsp;J.&nbsp;Schumacher, $266,243; and, J.&nbsp;V.&nbsp;Mazzo, $50,589. As Messrs.&nbsp;White and Freyman are eligible to retire, each
of them would be eligible to begin to receive the pension benefits described on pages&nbsp;30 to 32. If the termination of employment was due to disability, then the following named officers also
would have received, in addition to Abbott's standard disability benefits, a monthly long-term disability benefit in the amount of $162,500 for M.&nbsp;D.&nbsp;White; $53,583 for
T.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Freyman; $44,792 for L.&nbsp;J.&nbsp;Schumacher, and $14,542 for J.&nbsp;V.&nbsp;Mazzo. This long-term disability benefit would continue for up to
18&nbsp;months following termination of employment. It ends if the officer retires, recovers, dies or ceases to meet eligibility criteria. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
addition, if the named officer's employment (including Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon's) had terminated due to death or disability, the officer's unvested stock options and restricted shares would have vested
on December&nbsp;31, 2009 with values as set forth below in the section captioned, "Accelerated Vesting of Equity Awards." </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Abbott's
French employees, including Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon, are covered by collective bargaining agreements. As an employee covered by a collective bargaining agreement, if his employment is terminated by
Abbott for any reason, other than gross or willful misconduct, Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon is entitled to a lump sum cash payment equal to: (i)&nbsp;one-third of the monthly average of the
aggregate of his base salary at the time of termination, the bonus he was paid and certain other benefits he received during the preceding twelve-month period, multiplied by his years of
service with the company, not to exceed the amount of the total cash compensation paid to him during the preceding twelve months, plus (ii)&nbsp;three months of base salary, based on the average
salary he received over the last 12&nbsp;months prior to his termination or any higher amount if it corresponds to the salary he would have received during the notice period under the agreement if
he is released from performing the services, plus (iii)&nbsp;accrued but unpaid vacation time up until the end of the notice period. In addition, he would be entitled to coverage under Abbott's
health and welfare benefits plans for nine months following the date of termination. If Mr.&nbsp;Bohoun's employment had terminated as described above on December&nbsp;31, 2009, he would have been
entitled to receive a cash payment of $636,962 and health and welfare benefits of $15,285. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Potential Payments Upon Change in Control  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Messrs.&nbsp;White, Freyman, and Bohuon do not have change in control agreements with Abbott. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Abbott
has change in control arrangements with the rest of its management team, in the form of change in control agreements for Abbott officers and a change in control plan for other key management
personnel. The agreements with Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher, and Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo, are described below. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
agreements with Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher, and Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo, continue in effect until December&nbsp;31, 2012, and at the end of each year will automatically be extended through the third year
thereafter unless Abbott notifies the officer that the agreement will not be extended. The agreements also automatically extend for two years following any change in control (see below) that occurs
while they are in effect. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
agreements provide that if the officer is terminated other than for cause or permanent disability or if the officer elects to terminate employment for good reason (see below) or within two years
following a change in control of Abbott (including termination by the officer for any reason during the thirty-day window period which begins six months after the date of a change in
control), the officer is
entitled to receive a lump sum payment equal to three times the officer's annual salary and annual incentive ("bonus") award (assuming for this purpose that all target performance goals have been
achieved or, if higher, based on the average bonus for the last three years), plus any unpaid bonus owing for any completed performance period and the pro rata bonus for any current bonus period
(based on the highest of the bonus assuming achievement of target performance, the average bonus for the past three years, or in the case of the unpaid bonus for any completed performance period, the
actual bonus earned). If the officer is terminated other </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>34</FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=39,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=75558,FOLIO='34',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EI44701A.;27',USER='LSMITH',CD=';6-MAR-2010;09:01' -->
<A NAME="page_ei44701_1_35"> </A>
<BR>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
than for cause or permanent disability or if the officer elects to terminate employment for good reason during a potential change in control (see below), the officer is entitled to receive a lump sum
payment of the annual salary and bonus payments described above, except that the amount of the bonus to which the officer is entitled will be based on the actual achievement of the applicable
performance goals. If the potential change in control becomes a "change in control event" (within the meaning of Section&nbsp;409A of the Internal Revenue Code), the officer will be entitled to
receive the difference between the bonus amounts the officer received upon termination during the potential change in control and the bonus amounts that would have been received had such amounts
instead been based on the higher of the officer's target bonus or the average bonus paid to the officer in the preceding three years. Bonus payments include payments made under the Performance
Incentive Plan. The officer will also receive up to three years of additional employee benefits (including welfare benefits; three years of outplacement services and tax and financial counseling; and
the value of three more years of pension accruals), and payment of any excise taxes imposed under Section&nbsp;4999 of the Internal Revenue Code and other related taxes for which the officer is
responsible as a result of receiving payments and benefits in connection with a change in control. The agreements also limit the conduct for which awards under Abbott's incentive stock programs can be
terminated and generally permit options to remain exercisable for the remainder of their term. Independent compensation consultants confirm that the level of payments provided under the agreements is
consistent with current market practice. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
purposes of the agreements, the term "change in control" includes the following events: any person becoming the beneficial owner of Abbott securities representing twenty percent or more of the
outstanding voting power (not including an acquisition directly from Abbott and its affiliates); a change in the majority of the members of the board of directors whose appointment was approved by a
vote of at least two-thirds of the incumbent directors; and the consummation of certain mergers or similar corporate transactions involving Abbott. A "potential change in control" under
the agreements includes, among other things, Abbott's entry into an agreement that would result in a change in control. Finally, the term "good reason" includes: a significant adverse change in the
executive's position, duties, or authority; the company's failure to pay the executive's compensation or a reduction in the executive's base pay or benefits; or the relocation of the company's
principal executive offices to a location that is more than thirty-five miles from the location of the offices at the time of the change in control. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>If
a change in control had occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2009, immediately followed by one of the covered circumstances described above, Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher and Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo would have been
entitled to receive the following payments and benefits under the change in control agreements: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher,
Cash termination payments&nbsp;&#150; $6,710,200; Additional Supplemental Pension Plan benefits&nbsp;&#150; $656,231; Welfare and
fringe benefits&nbsp;&#150; $105,000; Excise tax reimbursements&nbsp;&#150; $2,860,214.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo,
Cash termination payments&nbsp;&#150; $3,721,001; Additional Supplemental Pension Plan benefits&nbsp;&#150; $496,539; Welfare and fringe
benefits&nbsp;&#150; $105,000. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>To
determine the amount of the officer's excise tax reimbursement, Abbott has assumed that the named officer pays taxes at the highest marginal tax rate; that the price of an Abbott common share is
equal to the closing price of an Abbott common share on December&nbsp;31, 2009; and that a portion of the payments and benefits is not subject to excise tax. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Accelerated Vesting of Equity Awards  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Under the Abbott Laboratories' Incentive Stock Programs, upon a change in control, all outstanding stock options, restricted stock and restricted stock units vest, including
performance-based restricted shares, which are deemed earned in full. If a change in control had occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2009: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;White
would have vested (1)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 861,666 unvested stock options with a value of $265,833, and (2)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 366,666
restricted shares with a value equal to $19,796,297.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Freyman
would have vested (1)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 230,533 unvested stock options with a value of $54,133, and (2)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 127,333
restricted shares with a value equal to $6,874,709.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Bohuon
would have vested (1)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 157,700 unvested stock options with a value of $163,512, and (2)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 85,666
restricted shares with a value equal to $4,625,107.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Ms.&nbsp;Schumacher
would have vested (1)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 175,899 unvested stock options with a value of $54,133, and (2)&nbsp;in an aggregate of 104,133
restricted shares with a value equal to $5,622,141.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Mazzo
would have vested in an aggregate of 50,000 restricted shares with a value equal to $2,699,500. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
value of stock options shown is based on the excess of the closing price of an Abbott common share on December&nbsp;31, 2009 over the exercise price of such options, multiplied by the number of
unvested stock options held by the named officer. The value of restricted shares shown is determined by multiplying the number of restricted shares that would vest as of December&nbsp;31, 2009 and
the closing price of an Abbott common share on December&nbsp;31, 2009. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Approval Process for Related Person Transactions  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
It is Abbott's policy that the nominations and governance committee review, approve or ratify any transaction in which Abbott participates and in which any related person has a direct or indirect
material interest if such transaction involves or is expected to involve payments of $120,000 or more in the aggregate per fiscal year. Related person transactions requiring review by the nominations
and governance committee pursuant to this policy are identified in: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>questionnaires
annually distributed to Abbott's directors and officers,
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>certifications
submitted annually by Abbott officers related to their compliance with Abbott's Code of Business Conduct, or
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>communications
made directly by the related person to the chief financial officer or general counsel. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
determining whether to approve or ratify a related person transaction, the nominations and governance committee will consider the following items, among others: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>the
related person's relationship to Abbott and interest in the transaction;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>the
material facts of the transaction, including the aggregate value of such transaction or, in the case of indebtedness, the amount of principal involved;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>the
benefits to Abbott of the transaction;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>if
applicable, the availability of other sources of comparable products or services;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>an
assessment of whether the transaction is on terms that are comparable to the terms available to an unrelated third party or to employees generally;
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>whether
a transaction has the potential to impair director independence; and
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>whether
the transaction constitutes a conflict of interest. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>This
process is included in the nominations and governance committee's written charter, which is available on the corporate governance section of Abbott's investor relations Web site
(www.abbottinvestor.com). Abbott did not have any related person transactions in 2009 requiring nominations and governance committee approval under this policy. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>36</FONT></P>

<A NAME="page_ek44701_1_37"> </A>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Ratification of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP as Auditors (Item&nbsp;2 on Proxy Card)  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Abbott's bylaws provide that the audit committee shall appoint annually a firm of independent registered public accountants to serve as auditors. In October 2009, the audit committee appointed
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP to act as auditors for 2010. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP has served as Abbott's auditors since 2002. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Although
the audit committee has sole authority to appoint auditors, it would like to know the opinion of the shareholders regarding its appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP as auditors
for 2010. For this reason, shareholders are being asked to ratify this appointment. If the shareholders do not ratify the appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP as auditors for 2010, the
audit committee will take that fact into consideration, but may, nevertheless, continue to retain Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=3><B>The board of directors recommends a vote FOR ratification of the appointment of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP as auditors for
2010.</B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Representatives of Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche&nbsp;LLP are expected to be present at the Annual Meeting and will be given the opportunity to make a statement if they desire to
do so. They will also be available to respond to appropriate questions. </FONT></P>

Entities during these periods. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><B>Policy on Audit Committee Pre-Approval of Audit and Permissible Non-Audit Services of the Independent Auditor  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The audit committee has established policies and procedures to pre-approve all audit and permissible non-audit services performed by the Deloitte Entities. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Prior
to engagement of the independent registered public accounting firm for the next year's audit, management will submit a schedule of all proposed services expected to be rendered during that year
for each of four categories of services to the audit committee for approval. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Prior
to engagement, the audit committee pre-approves these services by category of service. The fees are budgeted and the audit committee requires the independent registered public
accounting firm and management to report actual fees versus the budget periodically by category of service. During the year, circumstances may arise when it may become necessary to engage the
independent registered public accounting firm for additional services not contemplated in the original pre-approval. In those instances, the audit committee requires specific
pre-approval before engaging the independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
audit committee may delegate pre-approval authority to one or more of its members. The member to whom such authority is delegated must report any pre-approval decisions to
the audit committee at its next scheduled meeting. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>37</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Report of the Audit Committee  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Management
is responsible for Abbott's internal controls and the financial reporting process. The independent registered public accounting firm is responsible for performing an audit of the
consolidated financial statements and expressing an opinion on the conformity of those financial statements with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America, as well as
expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting. The Audit Committee reviews these processes on behalf of the Board of Directors. In this context, the committee
has reviewed and discussed the audited financial statements contained in the 2009 Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K with Abbott's management and its independent registered public
accounting firm. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
committee has discussed with the independent registered public accounting firm the matters required to be discussed by the Statement on Auditing Standards No.&nbsp;61
(</FONT><FONT SIZE=2><I>Communication with Audit Committees</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>), as amended, as adopted by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
committee has received the written disclosures and the letter from the independent registered public accounting firm required by the applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting
Oversight Board regarding the independent registered public accounting firm's communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence, and has discussed with the independent registered public
accounting firm their independence. The committee has also considered whether the provision of the services described on page&nbsp;37 under the caption "Audit Fees and Non-Audit Fees" is
compatible with maintaining the independence of the independent registered public accounting firm. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Based
on the review and discussions referred to above, the committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the audited financial statements be included in Abbott's Annual Report on
Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2009 filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2><I><U>Audit Committee</U>  </I></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>R. S. Austin, Chair, D. A. L. Owen, S. C. Scott III, W. D. Smithburg, and G. F. Tilton </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting Compliance  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Abbott believes that during 2009 its officers and directors complied with all filing requirements under Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. </FONT></P>

 </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Shareholder Proposal on Advisory Vote (Item&nbsp;3 on Proxy Card)  </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The Unitarian Universalist Association of Congregations, 25 Beacon Street, Boston, MA 02108 and three other proponents have informed Abbott that they intend to present the following proposal at the
meeting. Abbott will provide the proponents' names and addresses to any shareholder who requests that information and, if provided by a proponent to Abbott, the number of Abbott common shares held by
that proponent. The proposal should be opposed in our Proxy Statement. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>RESOLVED
&#150; the shareholders of Abbott Labs,&nbsp;Inc. recommend that the board of directors adopt a policy requiring that the proxy statement for each annual meeting contain a proposal,
submitted by and supported by Company Management, seeking an advisory vote of shareholders to ratify and approve the board Compensation's Committee Report and the executive compensation policies and
practices set forth in the Company's Compensation Discussion and Analysis. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Proponents' Statement in Support of Shareholder Proposal  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Investors are increasingly concerned about mushrooming executive compensation especially when it is insufficiently linked to performance </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
2009 shareholders filed close to 100 "Say on Pay" resolutions. Votes on these resolutions averaged more than 46% in favor, and close to 25 companies had votes over 50% demonstrating strong
shareholder support for this reform. Investor, public and legislative concerns about executive compensation have reached new levels of intensity. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>An
Advisory Vote establishes an annual referendum process for shareholders about senior executive compensation. We believe this vote would provide our board and management useful information from
shareholders on the company's senior executive compensation especially when tied to an innovative investor communication program. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>In
2008 Aflac submitted an Advisory Vote resulting in a 93% vote in favor, indicating strong investor support for good disclosure and a reasonable compensation package. Chairman and CEO Daniel Amos
said, "An advisory vote on our compensation report is a helpful avenue for our shareholders to provide feedback on our pay-for-performance compensation philosophy and pay
package." </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Over
30 companies have agreed to an Advisory Vote, including Apple, Ingersoll Rand, Microsoft, Occidental Petroleum, Pfizer, Prudential, Hewlett-Packard, Intel, Verizon, MBIA, and PG&amp;E. And nearly 300
TARP participants implemented the Advisory Vote in 2009, providing an opportunity to see it in action. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Influential
proxy voting service RiskMetrics Group, recommends votes in favor, noting "RiskMetrics encourages companies to allow shareholders to express their opinions of executive compensation
practices by establishing an annual referendum process. An advisory vote on executive compensation is another step forward in enhancing board accountability." </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>A
bill mandating annual advisory votes passed the House of Representatives, and similar legislation is expected to pass in the Senate. However, we believe companies should demonstrate leadership and
proactively adopt this reform before the law requires it. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
believe existing SEC rules and stock exchange listing standards do not provide shareholders with sufficient mechanisms for providing input to boards on senior executive compensation. In contrast,
in the United Kingdom, public companies allow shareholders to cast a vote on the "directors' remuneration report," which discloses executive compensation. Such a vote isn't binding, but gives
shareholders a clear voice that could help shape senior executive compensation. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
believe voting against the election of Board members to send a message about executive compensation is a blunt, sledgehammer approach, whereas an Advisory Vote provides shareowners a more effective
instrument. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
believe that a company that has a clearly explained compensation philosophy and metrics, reasonably links pay to performance, and communicates effectively to investors would find a management
sponsored Advisory Vote a helpful tool. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Board of Directors' Statement in Opposition to the Shareholder Proposal on Advisory Vote (Item&nbsp;3 on Proxy Card)  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The fundamental principle of corporate governance is to provide shareholders with an independent oversight body to govern a company for the benefit of its shareholders. Abbott's independent Board of
Directors is responsible for all aspects of governance, including compensation for executives, as well as Abbott's equity-based plans for all of Abbott's employees. Abbott has extremely robust
governance practices, which include executive compensation programs that are closely aligned with shareholder interests and annual grants of stock with performance vesting requirements. Shareholders
have recognized these attributes of Abbott's governance and executive compensation practices and have rejected this proposal each of the last three times it has been presented. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>An
advisory vote would ask shareholders to endorse or reject compensation decisions without the benefit of all the relevant information available to the Board of Directors, or to the Compensation
Committee members, or the benefit of their expertise. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>39</FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=44,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=972620,FOLIO='39',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EO44701A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD=';6-MAR-2010;02:20' -->
<A NAME="page_eo44701_1_40"> </A>
<BR>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The Compensation Committee, composed entirely of independent directors, is responsible for bringing its knowledge and skill to the process of reviewing, approving and overseeing Abbott's compensation
plans and practices. The Committee determines executive compensation only after considering a multitude of factors, including the strategic and financial objectives of Abbott and the performance of
the individuals involved. The Committee considers both public and confidential information. In this process, the Committee uses comparative market data from dozens of other companies and retains
advisors, as appropriate, to provide expert advice on compensation variables and levels. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Compensation Committee has determined that an executive compensation program designed around various elements of compensation, which includes base salaries, incentive bonuses, and various
performance-based equity awards, best meets its dual objectives of retaining highly talented executives and aligning compensation with shareholder returns. This program promotes the best interests of
shareholders. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
advisory vote called for by the proponent will not enhance Abbott's governance practices or improve accountability or communication with shareholders. Abbott has various accountability mechanisms
in place, such as its majority voting requirement and adherence to SEC rules requiring significant disclosure of compensation decisions and a comprehensive discussion of executive pay; as well as SEC,
NYSE, and IRS independence requirements for compensation committee members. Additionally, Abbott has established procedures to provide shareholders with a means to communicate directly with Board and
Committee members on any issue, including executive compensation. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Moreover,
the U.S. Congress is considering legislation requiring an advisory vote on executive compensation. It would be premature for Abbott to implement a shareholder advisory vote procedure at this
time because aspects of the procedure may be inconsistent with federal legislation and the procedures may be superseded before they could be implemented. The Board believes that Abbott and its
shareholders are best served by monitoring legislative developments and promptly adopting any new practices related to executive compensation and shareholder advisory votes that are mandated by law or
regulation and applied to all companies equally. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>For
the foregoing reasons, the Board of Directors believes that an advisory vote is not in the best interests of Abbott's shareholders and is not in the best interests of Abbott. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=4><B>The board of directors recommends that you vote AGAINST the proposal.  </B></FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P ALIGN="RIGHT" style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>40</FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=45,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=697526,FOLIO='40',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EO44701A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD=';6-MAR-2010;02:20' -->
<A NAME="page_eo44701_1_41"> </A>
<BR>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=8>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Shareholder Proposal on Special Shareholder Meetings (Item&nbsp;4 on Proxy Card)  </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
Kenneth Steiner, 14 Stoner Avenue, 2M, Great Neck, New York 10021, has informed Abbott that he intends to present the following proposal at the meeting and that he owns 1,000 Abbott common shares. The
proposal should be opposed in our Proxy Statement. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>RESOLVED,
Shareowners ask our board to take the steps necessary to amend our bylaws and each appropriate governing document to give holders of 10% of our outstanding common stock (or the lowest
percentage allowed by law above 10%) the power to call a special shareowner meeting. This includes that a large number of small shareowners can combine their holdings to equal the above 10% of
holders. This includes that such bylaw and/or charter text will not have any exception or exclusion conditions (to the fullest extent permitted by state law) that apply only to shareowners but not to
management and/or the board. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Proponent's Statement in Support of Shareholder Proposal  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
A special meeting allows shareowners to vote on important matters, such as electing new directors that can arise between annual meetings. If shareowners cannot call a special meeting investor returns
may suffer. Shareowners should have the ability to call a special meeting when a matter merits prompt attention. This proposal does not impact our board's current power to call a special meeting. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>This
proposal topic won more than 60% support at the following companies in 2009: CVS Caremark (CVS), Sprint Nextel (S), Safeway (SWY), Motorola (MOT) and R. R. Donnelley (RRD). William Steiner and
Nick Rossi sponsored these proposals. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
merit of this Special Shareowner Meeting proposal should also be considered in the context of the need for improvements in our company's 2009 reported corporate governance status: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Corporate Library www.thecorporatelibrary.com, independent investment research firm rated our company "D" with "High Governance Risk" and "High Concern" in executive pay &#150;
$28&nbsp;million for our CEO Miles White. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>David
Anthony Llewellyn Owen, Laurance Fuller, William Smithburg and Ann Reynolds had 13 to 29-years long-tenure &#150; independence concern. Plus these directors were
assigned to 7 of 15 seats on our most important board committees. Plus, Ann Reynolds was designated as a "Flagged (Problem) Director" by The Corporate Library due to her directorship at Owens Corning,
which filed for bankruptcy. James Farrell was also designated as a "Flagged (Problem) Director" due to his directorship at UAL Corporation, which filed for bankruptcy. Robert Alpern owned only 75
shares. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>We
had no shareholder right to an independent board chairman or a lead director. Plus an 67% vote was required to amend our charter. We still had plurality voting. Shareholder proposals to address all
or some of these topics have received majority votes at other companies and each would be an excellent topic for our next annual meeting. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>The
above concerns show there is need for improvement. Please encourage our board to respond positively to this proposal: Special Shareowner Meetings &#150; Yes on 4. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT COLOR="#2B85FF" SIZE=2><B>Board of Directors' Statement in Opposition to the Shareholder Proposal on Special Shareholder Meetings (Item&nbsp;4 on Proxy Card)  </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>
The Company's By-Laws currently provide that a single shareholder or group of shareholders owning at least 20&nbsp;percent of Abbott's outstanding shares may call a special meeting of
shareholders. This percentage threshold for the calling of a special meeting of shareholders is also consistent with the Illinois Business Corporation Act. The Board believes that this ownership
threshold provides an appropriate balance between ensuring the Board's accountability to a large percentage of shareholders and enabling the Board and management to operate the Company effectively.
Reducing this threshold to 10&nbsp;percent would enable a small minority of shareholders, who may not be supported by or representative of the majority of shareholders, to unnecessarily divert
Company resources and time to matters that may be insignificant to the majority of shareholders or the long term strategic or financial goals of the Company. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Special
shareholder meetings should be called for extraordinary events that have time urgency and can not be postponed until the next annual meeting. Permitting holders of only 10&nbsp;percent of
Abbott's shares to call a special meeting for any purpose, at any time and as often as such shareholders wish, would impose significant administrative and financial burdens on Abbott, and distract the
management and Board from their proper focus of operating the business and maximizing financial returns. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Additionally,
Abbott's existing corporate governance policies and practices enable all shareholders to express their concerns on important matters. Under the proxy rules and the Company's
By-Laws, shareholders may submit proposals for inclusion in Abbott's proxy statement, nominate directors for election, and present matters from the floor at the annual meeting. Each of
Abbott's directors serves a one-year term and stands for re-election at the annual meeting. The Company's By-Laws also provide that directors must be elected by a
majority vote in an uncontested election. Abbott's corporate governance documents do not contain super-majority voting provisions and Abbott does not have a shareholder rights plan (poison pill). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>As
described elsewhere in this proxy statement, shareholders also may communicate directly with the Board of Directors on important matters pertaining to Abbott's business. </FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>41</FONT></P>

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=46,EFW="2196602",CP="ABBOTT LABORATORIES",DN="1",CHK=38693,FOLIO='41',FILE='DISK133:[09ZCA1.09ZCA44701]EO44701A.;14',USER='DBEMBEN',CD=';6-MAR-2010;02:20' -->
<A NAME="page_eo44701_1_42"> </A>
<BR>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=2>Accordingly,
the Board believes that Abbott's current By-Laws and governance practices ensure accountability to shareholders and enable the Board and management to operate Abbott
effectively. Approval of this proposal is neither necessary nor advisable. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:;"><FONT SIZE=4><B>The board of directors recommends that you vote AGAINST the proposal.  </B></FONT></P>
